From the table we can see that Physical and Mental health have a higher percentage of zeros. This means that just over 70% of the people in our data set are not physically active while about 60% of the respondents do not report having mental health issues.

We can also see that there are no N/A values in our data set. This is not surprising because our source data was cleaned before.

Finding the mean of numerical variables grouped by heart disease

plot_num(heart)
## Warning: `guides(<scale> = FALSE)` is deprecated. Please use `guides(<scale> =
## "none")` instead.

heart %>%
  group_by(HeartDisease) %>%
  summarise_at(vars("BMI", 
                    "PhysicalHealth", 
                    "MentalHealth",
                    "SleepTime"), mean)
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   HeartDisease   BMI PhysicalHealth MentalHealth SleepTime
##   <chr>        <dbl>          <dbl>        <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 No            28.2           2.96         3.83      7.09
## 2 Yes           29.4           7.81         4.64      7.14

On average, people with heart disease have a slightly higher BMI than those who dont have heart disease. However, the biggest difference is the number of days that a respondent feels physically unwell. HD people reported feeling physically unwell about 8 days per month, while healthy people felt unwell for only 3.

Are there differences between the means of the sexes

t.test(female$BMI, male$BMI)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  female$BMI and male$BMI
## t = -15.368, df = 318168, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.3866106 -0.2991518
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  28.16244  28.50532

The p-value is less than 0.05% significance level, allowing us to reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the overall average BMI is different between the male and female populations.

Is there a difference between the sex with heart disease

female_HD<- subset(female, HeartDisease==1)
male_HD<- subset(male, HeartDisease== 1)

 sex_bmi <-t.test(female_HD$BMI, 
                  male_HD$BMI)
## Error in t.test.default(female_HD$BMI, male_HD$BMI): not enough 'x' observations

We see that there is no difference in average BMI between the men and women who do have heart disease.

Correlations not particularly strong heart disease and stroke seem correlated Diabetes is correlated with heart disease and Kidney disease. Less with Stroke. Skin cancer is not correlated with other diseases.

Determining Independence between Diseases

hea_as=table(heart$HeartDisease,heart$Asthma)
chi_1=chisq.test(hea_as)
chi_1
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  hea_as
## X-squared = 548.85, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
hea_dia=table(heart$HeartDisease,heart$Diabetic)
chi_2=chisq.test(hea_dia)
chi_2
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  hea_dia
## X-squared = 10151, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
hea_kid=table(heart$HeartDisease,heart$KidneyDisease)
chi_3=chisq.test(hea_kid)
chi_3
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  hea_kid
## X-squared = 6739.2, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
hea_skin=table(heart$HeartDisease,heart$SkinCancer)
chi_4=chisq.test(hea_skin)
chi_4
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  hea_skin
## X-squared = 2783.6, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
hea_stroke=table(heart$HeartDisease,heart$Stroke)
chi_5=chisq.test(hea_stroke)
chi_5
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  hea_stroke
## X-squared = 12386, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16

For all the chi^2 tests we performed above, the p-value<0.05. So all the above rejects null hypothesis. Every secondary illness (Diabetic,Asthma, Kidney disease and skin cancer) has a relationship with heart Disease.
